---

## The Custom Order Diamond: Why 7ct Is Different

### The Supply Reality

At 1ct, supply is effectively infinite for a buyer's purposes. At 2ct, there are dozens of GIA Excellent options at any quality tier. At 4ct, you have 30–50 stones across the specification range. At 7ct, you have seven.

This is not a temporary market condition. It is structural. A 7ct round brilliant requires rough crystal of 14–16 carats. At that size, diamond rough is extracted in quantities of single digits globally per week — and not all of it is suitable for a GIA Excellent round cut. Most 7ct-capable rough gets divided into multiple smaller stones or allocated to cushion and oval cuts that yield better carat recovery from irregular rough shapes.

The few 7ct rounds that do reach the market have, in most cases, already been examined by multiple dealers and rejected — or purchased privately before reaching retail listings. What you see on Blue Nile at 7ct is the residual inventory: stones that passed through private networks without selling.

### The Per-Carat Premium Progression

| Carat Weight | Grade | Per-Carat Price | Multiple vs 1ct |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1ct | G-VS2 GIA Excellent | $3,230 | 1× |
| 2ct | G-VS2 GIA Excellent | $8,245 | 2.6× |
| 3ct | G-VS2 GIA Excellent | ~$16,260 | 5.0× |
| 4ct | G-VS2 GIA Excellent | ~$17,823 | 5.5× |
| 5ct | E-VS2 GIA Excellent | $30,332 | 9.4× |
| 6ct | G-VS2 GIA Excellent | $31,118 | 9.6× |
| **7ct** | **G-VS2 GIA Excellent** | **$34,756** | **10.8×** |

The jump from 6ct to 7ct adds another 12% to the per-carat price for the same grade. This is not the steep step-change that happened from 4ct to 5ct — it is a continued upward drift as availability shrinks further. By 7ct, you are fully inside a market where per-carat pricing is set by negotiation on individual stones, not by a commodity curve.

